      <hedline>
        <hl1>Work-Release as Bridge</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Elizabeth Lubetkin Lipton (Women's City Club of New York) supports May 31 editorial endorsing work-release for women in prison for striking back at their abusive husbands</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Work-Release for Battered Women'' (editorial, May 31):</p>
        <p>More than 85 percent of women in prison have children at home who depend on them for financial and emotional support. For the families involved, the work-release program is an important transition -- a bridge back into society.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Work-Release for Battered Women'' (editorial, May 31):</p>
        <p>More than 85 percent of women in prison have children at home who depend on them for financial and emotional support. For the families involved, the work-release program is an important transition -- a bridge back into society.</p>
        <p>Women who strike back at their abusers do so typically after years of abuse. This is a far different category of violent crime from other kinds of violent crimes. These women should, on a selective basis, be allowed to take part in work-release programs. It will not only help individual women to re-enter society,  but it will be a boon to the children who rely on their care.</p>
        <p>ELIZABETH LUBETKIN LIPTON  President  Women's City Club of New York  New York, May 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
